{"type":"message","id":"d8da660b","parentId":"ef62ca95","timestamp":"2026-05-14T15:41:43.195Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_KnL58TTS3b2I64gWrUpgEPUG|fc_070d952017f8fedb016a05ed2c51ec8190bfc1db5b8c24fb57","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/features.md:27:    iOS and Android nodes with pairing, voice/chat, and rich device commands.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/features.md:40:- DM safety with allowlists and pairing\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/features.md:66:- iOS node with pairing, Canvas, camera, screen recording, location, and voice\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/features.md:67:- Android node with pairing, chat, voice, Canvas, camera, and device commands\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/multi-agent.md:207:- DM access control is **global per WhatsApp account** (pairing/allowlist), not per agent.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/multi-agent.md:344:              dmPolicy: \"pairing\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/architecture.md:41:- Provide a device identity in `connect`; pairing is **device‑based** (role `node`) and\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/architecture.md:42:  approval lives in the device pairing store.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/architecture.md:100:- New device IDs require pairing approval; the Gateway issues a **device token**\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/architecture.md:107:  explicit pairing approval.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/architecture.md:110:  pins paired metadata on reconnect and requires repair pairing for metadata\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/architecture.md:116:Details: [Gateway protocol](/gateway/protocol), [Pairing](/channels/pairing),\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/exec.md:161:`/exec` is only honored for **authorized senders** (channel allowlists/pairing plus `commands.useAccessGroups`).\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/browser.md:484:- Browser control is loopback-only; access flows through the Gateway’s auth or node pairing.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/browser-wsl2-windows-remote-cdp-troubleshooting.md:57:- token or pairing is missing\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/browser-wsl2-windows-remote-cdp-troubleshooting.md:153:- token auth or pairing is configured correctly\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/browser-wsl2-windows-remote-cdp-troubleshooting.md:183:- `pairing required`\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/browser-wsl2-windows-remote-cdp-troubleshooting.md:207:The setup is usually viable. The hard part is that browser transport, Control UI origin security, and token/pairing can each fail independently while looking similar from the user side.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/slash-commands.md:26:    - Directives are only applied for **authorized senders**. If `commands.allowFrom` is set, it is the only allowlist used; otherwise authorization comes from channel allowlists/pairing plus `commands.useAccessGroups`. Unauthorized senders see directives treated as plain text.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/slash-commands.md:96:  Sets the explicit owner allowlist for owner-only command/tool surfaces. This is the human operator account that can approve dangerous actions and run commands such as `/diagnostics`, `/export-trajectory`, and `/config`. It is separate from `commands.allowFrom` and from DM pairing access.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/slash-commands.md:108:  Per-provider allowlist for command authorization. When configured, it is the only authorization source for commands and directives (channel allowlists/pairing and `commands.useAccessGroups` are ignored). Use `\"*\"` for a global default; provider-specific keys override it.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/slash-commands.md:224:- `/pair [qr|status|pending|approve|cleanup|notify]` manages device pairing/setup flow. See [Pairing](/channels/pairing).\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/plugin.md:126:visible plugin without importing runtime code or repairing dependencies.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/subagents.md:530:`scope-upgrade`, check the RPC caller before editing pairing state.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/logging.md:76:If the implicit local loopback Gateway asks for pairing, closes during connect,\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:908:    Security reminder: pairing a macOS node allows `system.run` on that machine. Only\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:974:    - **No inbound SSH required.** Nodes connect out to the Gateway WebSocket and use device pairing.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1634:    - Channel pairing/allowlist blocking replies (check channel config + logs).\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1762:    - Default behavior on DM-capable channels is **pairing**:\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1763:      - Unknown senders receive a pairing code; the bot does not process their message.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1764:      - Approve with: `openclaw pairing approve --channel <channel> [--account <id>] <code>`\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1765:      - Pending requests are capped at **3 per channel**; check `openclaw pairing list --channel <channel> [--account <id>]` if a code didn't arrive.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1800:    Docs: [Security](/gateway/security), [Pairing](/channels/pairing).\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1807:    - Keep DMs in **pairing mode** or a tight allowlist.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1823:  <Accordion title=\"I ran /start in Telegram but did not get a pairing code\">\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1825:    `dmPolicy: \"pairing\"` is enabled. `/start` by itself doesn't generate a code.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1830:    openclaw pairing list telegram\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1838:  <Accordion title=\"WhatsApp: will it message my contacts? How does pairing work?\">\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1839:    No. Default WhatsApp DM policy is **pairing**. Unknown senders only get a pairing code and their message is **not processed**. OpenClaw only replies to chats it receives or to explicit sends you trigger.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1841:    Approve pairing with:\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1844:    openclaw pairing approve whatsapp <code>\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1850:    openclaw pairing list whatsapp\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/troubleshooting.md:111:    openclaw pairing list --channel <channel> [--account <id>]\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/troubleshooting.md:126:    - `pairing request` → sender is unapproved and waiting for DM pairing approval.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/troubleshooting.md:133:    - [/channels/pairing](/channels/pairing)\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/troubleshooting.md:227:    - `pairing` / `pending` → DM sender is not approved yet.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/testing.md:551:  - WebSocket/HTTP surfaces, node pairing, and heavier networking\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/testing.md:603:- Touching gateway networking / WS protocol / pairing: add `pnpm test:e2e`\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/network.md:2:summary: \"Network hub: gateway surfaces, pairing, discovery, and security\"\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/network.md:5:  - You are debugging local vs tailnet access or pairing\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/network.md:36:- [Pairing overview (DM + nodes)](/channels/pairing)\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/network.md:37:- [Gateway-owned node pairing](/gateway/pairing)\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/network.md:38:- [Devices CLI (pairing + token rotation)](/cli/devices)\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/network.md:39:- [Pairing CLI (DM approvals)](/cli/pairing)\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/network.md:43:- Direct local loopback connects can be auto-approved for pairing to keep\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/network.md:48:  explicit pairing approval.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/security/THREAT-MODEL-ATLAS.md:183:| **Description**         | Attacker intercepts pairing code during pairing grace period (1h for DM channel pairing, 5m for node pairing) |\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/security/THREAT-MODEL-ATLAS.md:185:| **Affected Components** | Device pairing system                                                                                         |\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/security/THREAT-MODEL-ATLAS.md:186:| **Current Mitigations** | 1h expiry (DM pairing) / 5m expiry (node pairing), codes sent via existing channel                            |\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/security/formal-verification.md:79:**Claim:** pairing requests respect TTL and pending-request caps.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/security/formal-verification.md:82:  - `make pairing`\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/security/formal-verification.md:83:  - `make pairing-cap`\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/security/formal-verification.md:85:  - `make pairing-negative`\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/security/formal-verification.md:86:  - `make pairing-cap-negative`\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/security/formal-verification.md:112:**Claim:** a pairing store should enforce `MaxPending` and idempotency even under interleavings (i.e., “check-then-write” must be atomic / locked; refresh shouldn’t create duplicates).\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/security/formal-verification.md:120:  - `make pairing-race` (atomic/locked cap check)\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/security/formal-verification.md:121:  - `make pairing-idempotency`\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/security/formal-verification.md:122:  - `make pairing-refresh`\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/security/formal-verification.md:123:  - `make pairing-refresh-race`\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/security/formal-verification.md:125:  - `make pairing-race-negative` (non-atomic begin/commit cap race)\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/security/formal-verification.md:126:  - `make pairing-idempotency-negative`\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/security/formal-verification.md:127:  - `make pairing-refresh-negative`\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/security/formal-verification.md:128:  - `make pairing-refresh-race-negative`\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/platforms/digitalocean.md:152:openclaw pairing list telegram\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/platforms/digitalocean.md:153:openclaw pairing approve telegram <CODE>\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/platforms/ios.md:2:summary: \"iOS node app: connect to the Gateway, pairing, canvas, and troubleshooting\"\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/platforms/ios.md:36:3. Approve the pairing request on the gateway host:\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/platforms/ios.md:43:If the app retries pairing with changed auth details (role/scopes/public key),\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/platforms/ios.md:54:      pairing: {\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/platforms/ios.md:62:This is disabled by default. It applies only to fresh `role: node` pairing with"}],"details":{"persistedDetailsTruncated":true,"originalDetailsBytesAtLeast":8193,"originalDetailKeys":["status","exitCode","durationMs","aggregated","cwd"],"status":"completed","cwd":"/root/.openclaw/workspace","exitCode":0},"isError":false,"timestamp":1778773303192}}
