{"type":"message","id":"f8a4d77e","parentId":"2913cae9","timestamp":"2026-05-14T15:41:51.551Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_9Dr1lmp7HoVF2HIcKQN6RpRC|fc_070d952017f8fedb016a05ed3d37f08190ab75e543f500e454","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/multi-agent.md:198:      dmPolicy: \"allowlist\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/multi-agent.md:344:              dmPolicy: \"pairing\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/multi-agent.md:348:              dmPolicy: \"allowlist\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq-first-run.md:739:    Yes, via **multi-agent routing**. Bind each sender's WhatsApp **DM** (peer `kind: \"direct\"`, sender E.164 like `+15551234567`) to a different `agentId`, so each person gets their own workspace and session store. Replies still come from the **same WhatsApp account**, and DM access control (`channels.whatsapp.dmPolicy` / `channels.whatsapp.allowFrom`) is global per WhatsApp account. See [Multi-Agent Routing](/concepts/multi-agent) and [WhatsApp](/channels/whatsapp).\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1766:    - Opening DMs publicly requires explicit opt-in (`dmPolicy: \"open\"` and allowlist `\"*\"`).\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1825:    `dmPolicy: \"pairing\"` is enabled. `/start` by itself doesn't generate a code.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1833:    If you want immediate access, allowlist your sender id or set `dmPolicy: \"open\"`\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/config.md:201:      dmPolicy: \"disabled\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration.md:125:          dmPolicy: \"pairing\",   // pairing | allowlist | open | disabled\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration.md:164:    DM access is controlled per channel via `dmPolicy`:\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/audit-checks.md:110:| `security.exposure.open_channels_with_exec`                   | warn/critical | Shared/public rooms can reach exec-enabled agents                                    | `channels.*.dmPolicy`, `channels.*.groupPolicy`, `tools.exec.*`, `agents.list[].tools.exec.*`        | no       |\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:177:    whatsapp: { dmPolicy: \"pairing\", groups: { \"*\": { requireMention: true } } },\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:189:- Keep `dmPolicy: \"pairing\"` or strict allowlists.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:197:- **Trigger authorization**: who can trigger the agent (`dmPolicy`, `groupPolicy`, allowlists, mention gates).\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:525:All current DM-capable channels support a DM policy (`dmPolicy` or `*.dm.policy`) that gates inbound DMs **before** the message is processed:\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:571:  - When `dmPolicy=\"pairing\"`, approvals are written to the account-scoped pairing allowlist store under `~/.openclaw/credentials/` (`<channel>-allowFrom.json` for default account, `<channel>-<accountId>-allowFrom.json` for non-default accounts), merged with config allowlists.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:579:  - **Security note:** treat `dmPolicy=\"open\"` and `groupPolicy=\"open\"` as last-resort settings. They should be barely used; prefer pairing + allowlists unless you fully trust every member of the room.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:616:This does not replace the other hardening on this page — `dmPolicy`, allowlists, exec approvals, sandboxing, and `contextVisibility` still do the primary work. It closes one specific tokenizer-layer bypass against self-hosted stacks that forward user text with special tokens intact.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:1017:  channels: { whatsapp: { dmPolicy: \"pairing\" } },\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:1079:      dmPolicy: \"pairing\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:1278:3. **Freeze access:** switch risky DMs/groups to `dmPolicy: \"disabled\"` / require mentions, and remove `\"*\"` allow-all entries if you had them.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration-examples.md:183:      dmPolicy: \"pairing\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration-examples.md:535:If more than one person can DM your bot (multiple entries in `allowFrom`, pairing approvals for multiple people, or `dmPolicy: \"open\"`), enable **secure DM mode** so DMs from different senders don’t share one context by default:\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration-examples.md:545:      dmPolicy: \"allowlist\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration-examples.md:655:- If you set `dmPolicy: \"open\"`, the matching `allowFrom` list must include `\"*\"`.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-channels.md:117:      dmPolicy: \"pairing\", // pairing | allowlist | open | disabled\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-channels.md:154:- Per-account overrides: `channels.whatsapp.accounts.<id>.sendReadReceipts`, `channels.whatsapp.accounts.<id>.dmPolicy`, `channels.whatsapp.accounts.<id>.allowFrom`.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-channels.md:166:      dmPolicy: \"pairing\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-channels.md:250:      dmPolicy: \"pairing\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-channels.md:410:      dmPolicy: \"pairing\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-channels.md:512:      dmPolicy: \"pairing\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-channels.md:559:      dmPolicy: \"pairing\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-channels.md:585:      dmPolicy: \"pairing\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-channels.md:593:- Core key paths covered here: `channels.bluebubbles`, `channels.bluebubbles.dmPolicy`.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-channels.md:610:      dmPolicy: \"pairing\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-channels.md:720:      dmPolicy: \"pairing\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-channels.md:734:- Core key paths covered here: `channels.irc`, `channels.irc.dmPolicy`, `channels.irc.configWrites`, `channels.irc.nickserv.*`.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/install/macos-vm.md:164:      dmPolicy: \"allowlist\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/install/exe-dev.md:153:      dmPolicy: \"disabled\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/synology-chat.md:68:      dmPolicy: \"allowlist\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/synology-chat.md:94:- `dmPolicy: \"allowlist\"` is the recommended default.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/synology-chat.md:96:- In `allowlist` mode, an empty `allowedUserIds` list is treated as misconfiguration and the webhook route will not start (use `dmPolicy: \"open\"` with `allowedUserIds: [\"*\"]` for allow-all).\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/synology-chat.md:97:- `dmPolicy: \"open\"` allows public DMs only when `allowedUserIds` includes `\"*\"`; with restrictive entries, only matching users can chat.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/synology-chat.md:98:- `dmPolicy: \"disabled\"` blocks DMs.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/synology-chat.md:145:          dmPolicy: \"allowlist\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/synology-chat.md:160:- Prefer `dmPolicy: \"allowlist\"` for production.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/synology-chat.md:176:- `Allowlist is empty. Configure allowedUserIds or use dmPolicy=open with allowedUserIds=[\"*\"].`:\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/synology-chat.md:177:  - `dmPolicy=\"allowlist\"` is enabled but no users are configured\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/access-groups.md:66:      dmPolicy: \"allowlist\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/access-groups.md:70:      dmPolicy: \"allowlist\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/access-groups.md:112:      dmPolicy: \"allowlist\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/access-groups.md:146:      dmPolicy: \"allowlist\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/access-groups.md:168:- `dmPolicy: \"open\"` still requires `\"*\"` in the effective DM allowlist. Referencing an access group is not the same as public access.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/feishu.md:44:Configure `dmPolicy` to control who can DM the bot:\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/feishu.md:421:| `channels.feishu.dmPolicy`                        | DM policy                                                                        | `allowlist`      |\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/pairing.md:24:`dmPolicy: \"open\"` is public only when the effective DM allowlist includes `\"*\"`.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/pairing.md:71:    telegram: { dmPolicy: \"allowlist\", allowFrom: [\"accessGroup:operators\"] },\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/irc.md:43:- `channels.irc.dmPolicy` defaults to `\"pairing\"`.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/line.md:65:      dmPolicy: \"pairing\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/line.md:80:      dmPolicy: \"open\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/line.md:137:- `channels.line.dmPolicy`: `pairing | allowlist | open | disabled`\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/line.md:138:- `channels.line.allowFrom`: allowlisted LINE user IDs for DMs; `dmPolicy: \"open\"` requires `[\"*\"]`\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/zalouser.md:45:      dmPolicy: \"pairing\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/zalouser.md:82:`channels.zalouser.dmPolicy` supports: `pairing | allowlist | open | disabled` (default: `pairing`).\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/discord.md:427:    `channels.discord.dmPolicy` controls DM access. `channels.discord.allowFrom` is the canonical DM allowlist.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/discord.md:443:    Legacy `channels.discord.dm.policy` and `channels.discord.dm.allowFrom` still read for compatibility. `openclaw doctor --fix` migrates them to `dmPolicy` and `allowFrom` when it can do so without changing access.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/discord.md:473:      dmPolicy: \"allowlist\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/discord.md:496:      dmPolicy: \"allowlist\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/discord.md:516:      dmPolicy: \"allowlist\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/discord.md:1341:    - DM policy disabled: `channels.discord.dmPolicy=\"disabled\"` (legacy: `channels.discord.dm.policy`)\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/nostr.md:83:| `dmPolicy`   | string   | `pairing`                                   | DM access policy                    |\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/nostr.md:142:      dmPolicy: \"allowlist\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/telegram.md:40:      dmPolicy: \"pairing\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/telegram.md:107:    `channels.telegram.dmPolicy` controls direct message access:\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/telegram.md:114:    `dmPolicy: \"open\"` with `allowFrom: [\"*\"]` lets any Telegram account that finds or guesses the bot username command the bot. Use it only for intentionally public bots with tightly restricted tools; one-owner bots should use `allowlist` with numeric user IDs.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/telegram.md:118:    `dmPolicy: \"allowlist\"` with empty `allowFrom` blocks all DMs and is rejected by config validation.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/telegram.md:121:    If you previously relied on pairing-store allowlist files, `openclaw doctor --fix` can recover entries into `channels.telegram.allowFrom` in allowlist flows (for example when `dmPolicy: \"allowlist\"` has no explicit IDs yet).\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/telegram.md:123:    For one-owner bots, prefer `dmPolicy: \"allowlist\"` with explicit numeric `allowFrom` IDs to keep access policy durable in config (instead of depending on previous pairing approvals).\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/telegram.md:708:    - Reaction events still respect Telegram access controls (`dmPolicy`, `allowFrom`, `groupPolicy`, `groupAllowFrom`); unauthorized senders are dropped.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/telegram.md:987:- access control: `dmPolicy`, `allowFrom`, `groupPolicy`, `groupAllowFrom`, `groups`, `groups.*.topics.*`, top-level `bindings[]` (`type: \"acp\"`)\n--- pairing docs\n---\nsummary: \"Pairing overview: approve who can DM you + which nodes can join\"\nread_when:\n  - Setting up DM access control\n  - Pairing a new iOS/Android node\n  - Reviewing OpenClaw security posture\ntitle: \"Pairing\"\n---\n\n“Pairing” is OpenClaw’s explicit access approval step.\nIt is used in two places:\n\n1. **DM pairing** (who is allowed to talk to the bot)\n2. **Node pairing** (which devices/nodes are allowed to join the gateway network)\n\nSecurity context: [Security](/gateway/security)\n\n## 1) DM pairing (inbound chat access)\n\nWhen a channel is configured with DM policy `pairing`, unknown senders get a short code and their message is **not processed** until you approve.\n\nDefault DM policies are documented in: [Security](/gateway/security)\n\n`dmPolicy: \"open\"` is public only when the effective DM allowlist includes `\"*\"`.\nSetup and validation require that wildcard for public-open configs. If existing\nstate contains `open` with concrete `allowFrom` entries, runtime still admits\nonly those senders, and pairing-store approvals do not widen `open` access.\n\nPairing codes:\n\n- 8 characters, uppercase, no ambiguous chars (`0O1I`).\n- **Expire after 1 hour**. The bot only sends the pairing message when a new request is created (roughly once per hour per sender).\n- Pending DM pairing requests are capped at **3 per channel** by default; additional requests are ignored until one expires or is approved.\n\n### Approve a sender\n\n```bash\nopenclaw pairing list telegram\nopenclaw pairing approve telegram <CODE>\n```\n\nIf no command owner is configured yet, approving a DM pairing code also bootstraps\n`commands.ownerAllowFrom` to the approved sender, such as `telegram:123456789`.\nThat gives first-time setups an explicit owner for privileged commands and exec\napproval prompts. After an owner exists, later pairing approvals only grant DM\naccess; they do not add more owners.\n\nSupported channels: `bluebubbles`, `discord`, `feishu`, `googlechat`, `imessage`, `irc`, `line`, `matrix`, `mattermost`, `msteams`, `nextcloud-talk`, `nostr`, `openclaw-weixin`, `signal`, `slack`, `synology-chat`, `telegram`, `twitch`, `whatsapp`, `zalo`, `zalouser`.\n\n### Reusable sender groups\n\nUse top-level `accessGroups` when the same trusted sender set should apply to\nmultiple message channels or to both DM and group allowlists.\n\nStatic groups use `type: \"message.senders\"` and are referenced with\n`accessGroup:<name>` from channel allowlists:\n\n```json5\n{\n  accessGroups: {\n    operators: {\n      type: \"message.senders\",\n      members: {\n        discord: [\"discord:123456789012345678\"],\n        telegram: [\"987654321\"],\n        whatsapp: [\"+15551234567\"],\n      },\n    },\n  },\n  channels: {\n    telegram: { dmPolicy: \"allowlist\", allowFrom: [\"accessGroup:operators\"] },\n    whatsapp: { groupPolicy: \"allowlist\", groupAllowFrom: [\"accessGroup:operators\"] },\n  },\n}\n```\n\nAccess groups are documented in detail here: [Access groups](/channels/access-groups)\n\n### Where the state lives\n\nStored under `~/.openclaw/credentials/`:\n\n- Pending requests: `<channel>-pairing.json`\n- Approved allowlist store:\n  - Default account: `<channel>-allowFrom.json`\n  - Non-default account: `<channel>-<accountId>-allowFrom.json`\n\nAccount scoping behavior:\n\n- Non-default accounts read/write only their scoped allowlist file.\n- Default account uses the channel-scoped unscoped allowlist file.\n\nTreat these as sensitive (they gate access to your assistant).\n\n<Note>\nThe pairing allowlist store is for DM access. Group authorization is separate.\nApproving a DM pairing code does not automatically allow that sender to run group[... 7170 more characters truncated]"}],"details":{"persistedDetailsTruncated":true,"originalDetailsBytesAtLeast":8193,"originalDetailKeys":["status","exitCode","durationMs","aggregated","cwd"],"status":"completed","cwd":"/root/.openclaw/workspace","exitCode":0},"isError":false,"timestamp":1778773311550}}
